<subsection xml:id="quick-practice-inf-limits" class="unnumbered">
<title>Quick practice</title>

<p><ol>
<li> <p> Compute <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to\infty} e^{x}</m>.</p> </li>

<li> <p> Compute <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to\infty} e^{-x}</m>.</p>
</li>

<li> <p> Compute <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to\infty}
\dfrac{1}{x}</m>.</p> </li>

<li> <p> Which is bigger as <m>x\to\infty</m> <m>e^{-x}</m> or
<m>\dfrac{1}{x}</m>? Hence, what is <m>f_\infty(x)</m> for <m>f(x) =
e^{-x}+\dfrac{1}{x}</m>?</p> </li>

</ol></p>

<p> Answers:
</p>

<p><ol>
<li> <p> <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to\infty} e^{x} = \infty</m>.</p>
</li>

<li> <p> <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to\infty} e^{-x} = 0</m>.</p> </li>

<li> <p> <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to\infty} \dfrac{1}{x} = 0</m>.</p>
</li>

<li> <p> Between the terms <m>e^{-x}</m> and <m>\dfrac{1}{x}</m>,
<m>e^{-x}</m> goes to zero faster which implies that <m>\dfrac{1}{x}</m>
is bigger as <m>x\to\infty</m>. Hence, for <m>f(x) =
e^{-x}+\dfrac{1}{x}</m>, the leading behavior at infinity is
<m>f_\infty(x) = \dfrac{1}{x}</m>. This means the contribution of the
exponential term to the graph of <m>f(x)</m> vanishes quickly and the
graph <sq>looks like</sq> the graph of just <m>f_\infty(x) =
\dfrac{1}{x}</m> as <m>x</m> gets large.</p> </li>

</ol></p>

</subsection>
